{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654769"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:54:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:54:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18631"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18631"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.03,0,0.62,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11363"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78395"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11363"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18631"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63757"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6810"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26376"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26683"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78395"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe apex of the lung is an important anatomical region where thoracic structures communicate with the neck. It has several key relationships with surrounding neurovascular structures.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the superior extent of the lung apex?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lies below the level of the clavicle","Extends to the level of the cricoid cartilage","Extends to the level of the hyoid bone","Projects 2-3 cm above the first rib","Projects 5-6 cm above the first rib"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProjects 2-3 cm above the first rib\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct description of how far the apex of the lung extends superiorly\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELies below the level of the clavicle\u003C/strong\u003E - The apex clearly projects above the clavicle into the neck\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtends to the level of the cricoid cartilage\u003C/strong\u003E - This would be too high in the neck for the lung apex\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtends to the level of the hyoid bone\u003C/strong\u003E - This would be far too superior for the lung apex\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProjects 5-6 cm above the first rib\u003C/strong\u003E - This would be an excessive superior extension\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe apex is covered by cervical pleura and the suprapleural membrane (Sibson\u0027s fascia). Important relations include the subclavian vessels which groove the apex as they pass over the first rib, and the brachial plexus which lies lateral to it.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The apex of the lung extends into the root of the neck through the thoracic inlet, rising 2-3 cm above the first rib.","The subclavian artery grooves the apex of the lung as it passes over the first rib.","The cervical pleura covers the apex of the lung and is reinforced by the suprapleural membrane (Sibson\u0027s fascia)."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63757"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"qu